	   <tr><td colspan=2>Alright, I can agree whole heartedly with point one. I can't state an opinion on point 2 because I've never had to deal with Verant directly.<br><br>I say go for it. The game is great, and the people who play it are, for the most part, great. I haven't regretted getting the game. I enjoy the interaction with people that I would otherwise never get to meet. Like, oh, my guildmate in Japan.<br><br>Things I like best about this game:<br>1. People. Like I said, you will meet all kinds of people you otherwise wouldn't. Most will be very helpful, giving buffs, binds and ports. Some even give away items they don't need any more.<br>2. Places. This is a very detailed world. I really like new zones they add because you can see where they figured out about elaborating. <br>3. Politics. Faction alliances give you a political depth to the game. If it is your style, you could probably play the game based just on getting your factions where you want them to be in each city.<br>4. Quests. There are lots of little quests that are great to do as you go along. They are basically extra xp and money for your kills. There are also some larger quests that are just great in what you get from them and while doing them. Like he said, you can replay these over and over. So, if there is a quest you really like, you can play it as often as you want.<br>5. Simplicity. You don't HAVE to purchase the expansions to play. These days, the game is inexpensive to buy. You get the trial month. blah blah blah. <br>6. GM's. My experiences with the GM's has been good. They help when they can. I've had a couple of instances where the GM's couldn't help. I've had a others where they could help, but they were back-logged and it took a while. And I've had a few where they helped almost right away. I've run into GM's doing...I have no idea what, but it was in Nek, and I was praying that it wasn't heralding an event...and they were very polite.<br>7. Events. I haven't been able to participate in one, but they happen. There are also player-formed guilds who will create their own events and raids. "newbie guilds" have started (we are one), which (not meaning to toot my own horn) I think is a good idea. <br><br>There are a few things I don't like.<br>1. People. Once in a while, you will run into someone who will totally ruin your night, or part of it. Be it rudeness, bullying, camp-stealing, or kill stealing (it won't take you long to figure out what those last two are) or people like, oh, me a couple of posts down, who were reacting to bad days (i apologize again, and most of those will too).<br>2. Response time. Sometimes the GMs are way too overloaded and there are too few of them. Response times can be really slow<br>3.<br><br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp; Lag. You'll get it, and sometimes it will hurt. Sometimes servers go down. But then, this is an online game, and part of a technology that is still being perfected. Really, it doesn't happen enough to spoil my fun<br>4. Events. Okay, there are alot of events that it will be a while before I can participate. Sucks, but when I think about it, there isn't a whole lot for a lvl 50+ to do. Let them have the events. Also there are some quests that will require the expansions. Really, they don't come until sometime after lvl 20, and they aren't anything you HAVE to do. It certainly won't detract from enjoyment if you don't do them. So, get the expansions when you want. The quests will still be there.<br><br>IMO, you will enjoy this game more than you will get frustrated. Even my fiance has learned to enjoy the game, and he got really frustrated and almost quit it at first.<br><br>Experiment with classes. I suggest Druid of whatever race for first class. I like elves the most, but I just like elves and fairy-kin. You might like another race more. Druids are the easiest to start with, I think. Experiment with classes and races,though, and decide what you like.<br><br>If you are on Qeullous, then give me a /tell<br><br>Tatiyanna<br><br>&nbsp;<br>"In waking a tiger, use a very long stick." -Mao Tse-Tung. Did he go to Stonebrunt too?</td></tr>
